<br>
Example one (This is my personal point of view only) with regard to ES 'requirement', which I think is admirable in philosophy. <br>
<br>
I am in a group with 5 quildies and a player from an outside group, all within one or two levels of each other, who happens to be doing a kick arsed job. A guildie comes on who is the same class as the other player but 5 levels lower. What do you do? Take the guildie, skew the XP and dump the other player (Which personally I feel is rude) or or appologize to the guildie, you are in a full group atm, but if a spot opens up will be sure to invite them. <br>
<br>
I love my guild and my guildies, but my personal choice would be to keep the group intact as it was. To me it's only fair to the 6 people who are already engaged in the battles. That being said we always look for a guildie to fill that spot first. Always. <br>
<br>
Example 2 Raiding VS Grouping. Is there a balance? I think there can be, however, I know nothing from personal experience about the 60+ game yet. Ideally, for me, what I would like to see with in my guild is a strong core group of people who can hold successful raids on a regular basis, but also have the time to group XP if they so choose. I don't feel that it has to be one or the other. <br>
<br>
Personally, I love to raid, I also love to group and sometimes I just want to sit in the Nexus and hang with my friends and not do anything. The guild I am in and have been in since shortly after I started playing the game is as close to ideal as I can see coming. <br>
<br>
We are also growing, with more 55+ people than we have had before, many of us having been with the guild since we were in our early levels. We have a strong sense of commitment to our fellow players and endeavour to strengthen the guild as a whole by doing alot of XP grouping in tough zones with fellow members. We choose this, it is not a requirement. By doing this, we have a terrific force of people to raid with. <br>
<br>
We're doing our first Hate raid soon. To many higher level guilds this will seem like a cake walk. To us it's a big deal and a big step for us. We're pretty damn proud of it too. We've worked hard, all of us. Our people who aren't quite high enough level to zone into hate have been working together constantly to achieve that goal. Personally I find that kind of team work impressive as heck. <br>
<br>
It's a quarter till two in the morning, so I am rambling a bit. Please forgive me.<br>
<br>
I guess my point is, grouping and raiding should be a part of any guild IMHO. I think it's possible, not always easy but possible.  <br>
<br>
<br>
This is true for any guild out there. A very wise person once said &quot;You can please all of the people some of time and some of the people all of the time, but you can't please all of the people all of the time.&quot; More true words were never spoken. <br>
<br>
I think we all have goals we would like to see achieved in the beginning. However, as the game changes we change with it. Our focus changes as our toons develop and people come and go along with those changes. It should all be good, there is after all something for everyone out there. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
